description:
## Goal

Make above-threshold constant bitstrings free at runtime: the entire SharedBin struct (40 bytes) lives in the program binary's `.data` section with a perpetual anchor refcount and the noop destructor. No `Box::new`, no byte memcpy, no per-call SharedBin allocation. Each invocation of code containing the literal pays only the cost of one 32-byte ProcBin allocation on the per-process heap.

Widen the const-fold pass so it accepts every statically-knowable bitstring shape: any size, any endianness, signed or unsigned integers, plus 32/64-bit float literals. Drive the runtime's `BitWriter` directly from the pass — same primitives, identical bit pattern.

## Depends on

fz-q8d.1 (destructor field + SharedBinHandle API).

## Codegen — static SharedBin emission

When the const-fold produces a `Prim::ConstBitstring(bytes, bit_len)` and `bytes.len() > SHARED_BIN_THRESHOLD_BYTES`:

1. Declare/intern bytes payload data symbol (existing path):
   ```rust
   let bytes_id = jmod.declare_data(&bytes_name, Linkage::Local, /*writable=*/false, /*tls=*/false)?;
   let mut bytes_desc = DataDescription::new();
   bytes_desc.define(bytes.clone().into_boxed_slice());
   bytes_desc.set_align(1);
   jmod.define_data(bytes_id, &bytes_desc)?;
   ```

2. Declare the noop destructor function symbol once per module:
   ```rust
   let noop_fn_id = jmod.declare_function(
       "shared_bin_destructor_noop",
       Linkage::Import,
       &runtime.shared_bin_destructor_noop_sig,
   )?;
   ```
   Cached so each module declares it once even with many static SharedBins.

3. Declare/intern the SharedBin struct data symbol (new):
   ```rust
   let sharedbin_id = jmod.declare_data(&sb_name, Linkage::Local, /*writable=*/true, /*tls=*/false)?;
   let mut sb_desc = DataDescription::new();
   // 40 bytes: refcount=1 (LE u64), bit_len (LE u64), bytes_ptr (relocation),
   //   bytes_len (LE u64), destructor (relocation)
   let mut buf = vec![0u8; 40];
   buf[0..8].copy_from_slice(&1u64.to_le_bytes());          // refcount anchor
   buf[8..16].copy_from_slice(&bit_len.to_le_bytes());
   buf[24..32].copy_from_slice(&(bytes.len() as u64).to_le_bytes());
   sb_desc.define(buf.into_boxed_slice());
   sb_desc.set_align(8);
   let bytes_gv = sb_desc.import_global_value(ModuleRelocTarget::Data(bytes_id));
   sb_desc.write_data_addr(16, bytes_gv, 0);
   let dest_fr = sb_desc.import_function(ModuleRelocTarget::Function(noop_fn_id));
   sb_desc.write_function_addr(32, dest_fr);
   jmod.define_data(sharedbin_id, &sb_desc)?;
   ```

4. Emit the call:
   ```rust
   let gv = jmod.declare_data_in_func(sharedbin_id, b.func);
   let sb_ptr = b.ins().symbol_value(types::I64, gv);
   let fref = jmod.declare_func_in_func(runtime.alloc_procbin_from_static_id, b.func);
   let inst = b.ins().call(fref, &[sb_ptr]);
   ```

Below-threshold const bitstrings: unchanged. Existing `fz_alloc_bitstring_const(ptr, byte_len, bit_len)` continues to handle them via `Heap::alloc_bitstring` → inline `HeapKind::Bitstring`.

## Codegen — cache shape

The existing per-module byte-payload cache is widened:

```rust
struct BsConstSyms { bytes_id: DataId, sharedbin_id: Option<DataId> }
let bs_const_data: RefCell<HashMap<Vec<u8>, BsConstSyms>> = ...;
```

Lookup: insert with `sharedbin_id = None` for below-threshold; `Some(id)` for above-threshold. Cache key by byte content so duplicate literals in the module share one set of symbols.

## Runtime — fz_alloc_procbin_from_static

```rust
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
pub extern "C" fn fz_alloc_procbin_from_static(static_sharedbin: u64) -> u64 {
    let sb = static_sharedbin as *mut SharedBin;
    let handle = unsafe { SharedBinHandle::retain_from_raw(sb) };
    let procbin = alloc_procbin(&mut current_process().heap, handle);
    crate::fz_value::FzValue::from_ptr(procbin.as_raw()).0
}
```

Retains the static SharedBin (refcount 1 → 2, anchor preserved), allocates a ProcBin, returns its tagged FzValue. When the ProcBin dies (MSO sweep or Heap::drop), `shared_bin_release` decrements refcount back to 1 (anchor). The noop destructor never runs in practice because the anchor keeps refcount > 0.

The runtime exports `shared_bin_destructor_noop` and `shared_bin_destructor_heap` as `#[unsafe(no_mangle)] pub extern "C"` symbols so codegen can take their addresses via `Linkage::Import`.

## Widened const-fold

`src/ir_const_bs.rs` is reworked to drive `BitWriter` at compile time:

```rust
fn try_fold(
    fields: &[BitFieldIr],
    int_const: &HashMap<Var, i64>,
    float_const: &HashMap<Var, f64>,
) -> Option<(Vec<u8>, u64)> {
    use fz_runtime::bitstr::{BitWriter, BitType, apply_endian_for_write};
    let mut w = BitWriter::new();
    for f in fields {
        let bits = match &f.size {
            Some(BitSizeIr::Literal(n)) => *n,
            _ => return None,
        };
        let unit = f.unit.unwrap_or(1);
        let total = bits * unit;
        if total == 0 || total > 64 { return None; }
        match f.ty {
            BitType::Integer => {
                let val = *int_const.get(&f.value)?;
                let masked = if total < 64 { (val as u64) & ((1u64 << total) - 1) } else { val as u64 };
                let swapped = apply_endian_for_write(masked, total, f.endian);
                w.write_bits(swapped, total as usize);
            }
            BitType::Float => {
                let val = *float_const.get(&f.value)?;
                let bits_repr = match total {
                    32 => (val as f32).to_bits() as u64,
                    64 => val.to_bits(),
                    _ => return None,
                };
                let swapped = apply_endian_for_write(bits_repr, total, f.endian);
                w.write_bits(swapped, total as usize);
            }
            _ => return None,  // Binary / Bits / Utf require runtime sources
        }
    }
    Some((w.bytes, w.bit_len as u64))
}
```

The float_const map is built analogously to int_const by collecting `Stmt::Let(v, Prim::Const(Const::Float(f)))`.

The pass continues to leave runtime-valued or runtime-sized fields alone — those keep the per-field `MakeBitstring` codegen path.

## Tests

- Fold widening:
  - 16-bit unsigned big-endian int literals → folds.
  - 32-bit signed little-endian int literals → folds (signed value masked correctly).
  - 64-bit float literal → folds.
  - 4-bit unsigned literals (bit-unaligned packing) → folds.
  - Mixed sizes within one literal (`<<a::16, b::8>>`) → folds.
  - Float with non-standard size (e.g. 16-bit) → does NOT fold (return None).
  - Mixed with one runtime field → does NOT fold.
- Codegen:
  - Below-threshold const bitstring (≤64 bytes): emits one call to `fz_alloc_bitstring_const(ptr, len, bit_len)`. No SharedBin symbol.
  - Above-threshold const bitstring (>64 bytes): emits the static SharedBin symbol with two relocations and one call to `fz_alloc_procbin_from_static(static_ptr)`. No `fz_bs_*` calls.
- Runtime:
  - `fz_alloc_procbin_from_static` retains the anchor, allocates a ProcBin pointing at it, deep_copy / send across processes still works (retains again).
  - The static SharedBin's refcount never reaches zero in normal operation; verify via a unit test that exercises spawn + send + GC and asserts the refcount stays ≥ 1.
- Three-path acceptance:
  - `fixtures/shared_heap_send_large_bitstring/` regenerated goldens reflect the new emission shape (one SharedBin data symbol per call site, one call to fz_alloc_procbin_from_static).
  - Fixture passes across `[jit, interp, aot]`. The interp branch for `Prim::ConstBitstring` is updated to recognise above-threshold const bitstrings: since interp doesn't emit Cranelift data, it has two reasonable paths:
    (a) Always memcpy via the existing `Heap::alloc_bitstring(bytes, bit_len)` — simplest, equivalent to today's behaviour for interp.
    (b) Cache a static SharedBin per (bytes, bit_len) keyed value in a process-wide table.
    Pick (a) — interp isn't a perf path, parity-by-behaviour is what matters. Output across the three paths is identical regardless of storage strategy because dispatch helpers abstract the kind.

## Acceptance

- All four fold-widening tests pass.
- Codegen golden for a small const bitstring (≤64) and a large const bitstring (>64) showing the two emission shapes.
- The fixture `fixtures/shared_heap_send_large_bitstring/` passes across `[jit, interp, aot]`.
- Compile-time output size for the large fixture shrinks again or stays the same (already 108 lines after fz-cty.8; the call site changes shape, the count stays similar).
- No regression: every existing fixture across the spec_parity suite passes unchanged or with mechanical golden updates (only call-site shape changes, not behaviour).
- Clippy and warnings clean.

## Non-changes

- `Heap::alloc_bitstring`'s threshold policy unchanged.
- The procbin module API unchanged from .1.
- AOT shim, scheduler, fz_send, fz_spawn: unaffected.
